The story of Deucalion and Pyrrha, and how men and women sprung up from the stones they threw behind them, is told at length by Ovid (Met. i. 260 sqq.). The mountain on which the vessel lauded is said by Ovid, and was generally supposed, to be Par- nassus 3 and the divinity whose oracle Deu- calion consulted, was Themis ‘ Sortes: for the answer of an oracle, is taken from the Italian practice, particularly in the temples of Fortuna, whose responses were delivered by lots (Cic.
